At 3 d of age, calves were assigned to treatments of ground (GS), pelleted (PS), or textured (TS) starters (four female and six male calves/treatment). The GS was a typical calf starter ration with oats (Table 1
). The PS and TS were typical commercial type starters with the same ingredients except that the TS contained oats. All starters were formulated to be isonitrogenous at 22% CP and all contained 0.07% lasalocid. The chemical composition of the starters is provided in Table 2
. Starter intake was determined daily, and BW were obtained weekly. Ad libitum water was provided for calves from 3 d of age throughout the study.

There was a significant (P = 0.005) treatment × week interaction for physical form of starter (Figure 3
). During wk 5, calves fed GS and TS consumed more (P
 < 0.05) starter at approximately 0.7 kg/d compared with calves consuming PS at approximately 0.4 kg/d. During wk 6, the difference in starter consumption between TS and PS increased, as a result of earlier weaning from whole milk, so that calves fed TS consumed approximately 35% more starter than calves fed PS. Calves fed TS, GS, and PS consumed an average of 1.4, 1.2, and 0.8 kg/d, respectively, during wk 6.
